#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:15
msgid "!!! note \"A few words about `mappings.lua`\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:17
#, no-wrap
msgid "    Throughtout NvChad's official documentation, commands such as `<leader>` are mentioned, along with other keys that might not be understandable to the casual reader. The reason for this is the default `mappings.lua` file (`../nvim/lua/core/mappings.lua`).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:19
#, no-wrap
msgid "    This file and the key mappings it describes are outlined [here](https://nvchad.com/docs/config/mappings). To be clear, you can override any key mappings using a custom `mappings.lua` file (`../nvim/lua/custom/mappings.lua`).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:21
#, no-wrap
msgid "    To avoid confusion in the documents you are now reading, we are going to assume that you are using the default `mappings.lua` file and will substitute in the actual commands that you need to use to access a function. Standard key references are:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    * '
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:26
msgid "leader = <kbd>SPACE</kbd>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    * '
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:26
msgid "A = <kbd>ALT</kbd>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    * '
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:26
msgid "C = <kbd>CTRL</kbd>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    * '
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:26
msgid "S = <kbd>SHFT</kbd>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:28
#, no-wrap
msgid "    If a command would specify `<leader>uu` as an example, we will substitute in the actual key combination of <kbd>SPACE</kbd><kbd>uu</kbd>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:30
#, no-wrap
msgid "    This will be covered again in the next section [Using NvChad](./using_nvchad.md)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:32
msgid ""
"Once Neovim is installed and the NvChad configuration is entered, our IDE "
"should look like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:34
msgid "![NvChad Default](../images/ui_default.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:36
msgid ""
"The interface already comes with some advanced functionality, such as "
"indicating the status of the git repository, but can be further enhanced by "
"using the Language Server, and customized by overriding some basic "
"configurations. The basic modules that make it up are detailed below."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:37
#, no-wrap
msgid "Tabufline"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:40
msgid "![Tabufline](../images/ui_tabufline.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:42
msgid ""
"The user interface presents a top bar called `Tabufline` where the open "
"buffers are managed. `Tabufline` only shows if you have more than one file "
"open. The open buffer presents the file type icon, the file name, and its "
"status. Status is indicated with an icon."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:44
#, no-wrap
msgid "If, as in the screenshot, we have a red `x`, it means that the file can be closed as it is already saved. If instead the icon is a green dot `.`, then the file needs to be saved, and a close command <kbd>SHIFT</kbd> + <kbd>:q</kbd> will produce a warning: \"No write since last change\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:46
msgid ""
"To the right is the icon for setting the _dark_ or _light_ theme. By "
"clicking on it with the mouse, we can select the theme we want."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:48
msgid "![NvChad Light](../images/ui_default_light.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:50
msgid "On the right we also have the icon for closing our editor."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:51
#, no-wrap
msgid "Middle Section - Open Buffers"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:54
msgid ""
"The central part of the editor is composed of the buffer active on the "
"editor at that moment (_index.en.md_). To introduce some additional "
"functionality, we can work simultaneously on two files in a split buffer by "
"opening one more in the example (_index.it.md_)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:56
#, no-wrap
msgid "In the editor we will have the first buffer in the foreground and the second one listed in the Tabufline. Now if we split the first buffer with the <kbd>SHIFT</kbd> + <kbd>:vsplit</kbd> command and select the right buffer, clicking on the name of the second file (_index.it.md_) in the tabufline, this will be opened in the right buffer and we can work with the two files side by side.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:58
msgid "![NvChad Split](../images/ui_nvchad_split.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:59
#, no-wrap
msgid "Statusline"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:62
msgid "![Statusline](../images/ui_statusline.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:64
msgid ""
"At the bottom we find the Statusline, which handles status information. On "
"the right we find the editor status. We must not forget that we are using a "
"text editor and that, in particular, it maintains the philosophy and "
"operation of Vim. The possible states are:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:69
msgid "- **NORMAL** - **INSERT** - **COMMAND** - **VISUAL**"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:71
#, no-wrap
msgid "Editing a document starts from the **NORMAL** mode where you open the file, then you can switch to **INSERT** mode for editing, and when finished exit with <kbd>ESC</kbd> and return to **NORMAL** mode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:73
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now to save the file you switch to **COMMAND** mode by typing `:` in the statusline followed by `w` (_write_) to write it and with <kbd>ESC</kbd> you return to **NORMAL** mode. The status indication is very useful while learning how to use it, particularly if one is not very familiar with the Vim workflow.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:75
msgid ""
"We then find the name of the open file, and if we are working on a git "
"repository, we will have indications of the status of the repository. This "
"is thanks to the _lewis6991/gitsigns.nvim_ plugin."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:77
msgid ""
"Turning to the right side we find the name of the folder from which we "
"opened the editor. In the case of the use of LSPs, this indicates the folder "
"that is taken into account as `workspace`, and consequently evaluated during "
"diagnostics, and to follow the position of the cursor within the file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:78
#, no-wrap
msgid "Integrated Help"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:81
msgid ""
"NvChad and Neovim provide some useful commands for displaying preset key "
"combinations and available options."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:83
#, no-wrap
msgid "If the <kbd>SPACE</kbd> key is pressed alone, it will provide a legend of associated commands as in the following screenshot:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:85
msgid "![Space Key](../images/ui_escape_key.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:87
#, no-wrap
msgid "To view all the commands included in the editor we can use the <kbd>SPACE</kbd> + <kbd>wK</kbd> command, which will give the following result:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:89
msgid "![leader wK](../images/ui_wK_key.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:91
#, no-wrap
msgid "And by pressing <kbd>d</kbd> we can display the remaining commands:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:93
msgid "![leader wK d](../images/ui_wK_01.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:95
msgid ""
"As we can see, almost all the commands refer to navigation within the "
"document or buffer. No commands for opening the file are included. These are "
"provided by the Neovim."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:97
#, no-wrap
msgid "To view all of Neovim's options, the <kbd>SHIFT</kbd> + <kbd>:options</kbd> command is available, which will present a tree of options indexed by category.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:99
msgid "![Nvim Options](../images/nvim_options.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:101
msgid ""
"This gives us a way, through the built-in help, to learn the commands while "
"using the editor, and also to delve into the available options."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:102
#, no-wrap
msgid "NvimTree"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:105
#, no-wrap
msgid "In order to work with our files we need a File Explorer, and this is provided by the _kyazdani42/nvim-tree.lua_ plugin. With the combination <kbd>CTRL</kbd> + <kbd>n</kbd> we can open NvimTree.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:107
msgid "![NvimTree](../images/nvim_tree.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:109
msgid ""
"A detailed description of NvimTree's commands and features can be found on "
"the [dedicated page](nvimtree.md)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/nvchad_ui/nvchad_ui.md:110
msgid ""
"Now that we have explored the interface components we can move on to using "
"NvChad."
msgstr ""
